this study was to obtain a database on the experience of adolescents/young 
adults with SCD that transfer to adult care. We assessed their treatment 
compliance, independence, and whether they receive uninterrupted care. Data were 
obtained through patient and provider interviews and patient record reviews. 
Results indicate patients leave pediatric care without adequate transfer 
preparation and readiness to transfer is not the major consideration in the 
decision to transfer, follow-up often ceases once the patients leave pediatric 
care, and patients who maintain follow-up appointments are more efficient in 
managing their illness (self-efficacy). The model for a structured transitioning 
process is provided with recommendations for nurse case managers to maintain 
follow-up.

