An evolutionary ecological perspective on demographic transitions: modeling 
multiple currencies.

Low BS(1), Simon CP, Anderson KG.

Author information:
(1)School of Natural Resources and Environment Population Studies Center, The 
University of Michigan, Ann Arbor, Michigan, USA.

Life history theory postulates tradeoffs of current versus future reproduction; 
today women face evolutionarily novel versions of these tradeoffs. Optimal age 
at first birth is the result of tradeoffs in fertility and mortality; ceteris 
paribus, early reproduction is advantageous. Yet modern women in developed 
nations experience relatively late first births; they appear to be trading off 
socioeconomic status and the paths to raised SES, education and work, against 
early fertility. Here, [1] using delineating parameter values drawn from data in 
the literature, we model these tradeoffs to determine how much socioeconomic 
advantage will compensate for delayed first births and lower lifetime fertility; 
and [2] we examine the effects of work and education on women's lifetime and 
age-specific fertility using data from seven cohorts in the Panel Study of 
Income Dynamics (PSID).

