Modelling death rates for carriers of hepatitis B.

Dickinson JA(1), Wun YT, Wong SL.

Author information:
(1)Department of Community and Family Medicine, The Chinese University of Hong 
Kong, 4/F School of Public Health, Prince of Wales Hospital, Shatin, NT.

Hepatitis B carriers who acquired the infection perinatally die from 
hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) and cirrhosis at high rates. Published cohort 
studies are largely limited to males and are too small to estimate the 
age-specific risk of death. We therefore used routinely collected Hong Kong data 
to estimate the risks. Deaths were partitioned between carriers and 
non-carriers, then current life table calculations determined life expectancy 
and probability of dying from HCC or cirrhosis. HCC is the dominant cause of 
death for male carriers in middle adulthood with a lifetime risk of 27% for HCC 
compared to 4% for females. Predicted life expectancy is 72 years for male 
carriers, compared to 79 years for non-carriers. Female carriers have a life 
expectancy of 81 years and non-carriers 83 years. This model probably applies to 
all southern Chinese populations and emigrants with similar life history, and 
other populations that acquired infection early in life.

